				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Hammarn wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The pet damage mitigation upgrade cut off roughly 20% of the damage done on my pet with the pet focus I had at that time - MoE. I did a quick parse to compare my own and my air pet's tanking just now, me with full tanking AA's but neglible worn effects, +8 avoidance and 1% shielding. 
<br />

<br />
RS air pet got hit 60.5% of the time for 37.1% on average, taking 32.6 DPS. 
<br />

<br />
I got hit 75% of the time for 45% on average, taking 47.8 DPS - the pet hence took around 70% of the damage I took tanking. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Just looked at the data I had taken pre and post mitigation patch for MoE focussed Air pets. Pre change pet took 61 dps against Blood Ravens, Post patch it took 38dps, 62% of the pre patch DPS. That seems at odds with your 20% figure.
<br />

<br />
Also just looked at how much DPS I take when tanking Blood Ravens (with 1187ac if that makes a difference) and I took 98 DPS!
<br />

<br />
So my findings say that MoE Air pet takes 39% of the damage that I do when tanking, yet again far different to your 70% figure.
<br />

<br />
As expected my pet tanks FAR better than I do.
<br />

<br />
Using my data (which I am sure is 100% correct) then a necro taking 280 dps would mean my pet is taking a mere 108 dps. To heal 108 DPS I'd only need to use PR (you forgot to include Heal foci I see) and would be able to nuke at the same time. Bet i'd use far less mana to kill those mobs than your necro would.
<br />

